headline: The BLS Is Closed. Here Are the Jobs Data the Fed Might Rely on Instead.
summary: The Federal government shutdown will suspend the flow of government-generated labor statistics, leaving investors and policymakers without the September jobs report, the latest Job Openings and Labor Turnover Survey (JOLTS), and updated wage data.  With the Bureau of Labor Statistics dark, Wall Street and the Federal Reserve are turning to private sources to track the strength of the labor market.  ADP’s monthly payroll report is considered the closest proxy for nonfarm payrolls, although its methodology often produces different results from the BLS counts.

headline: U.S. Lost Jobs in September, ADP Says. Why the Picture May Not Be So Bleak.
summary: The latest data show that employment in the private sector slid last month, a troubling sign that will be harder to parse because the government shutdown means other job-market indicators aren’t likely to be available.  The U.S. shed 32,000 jobs from private payrolls last month, according to the ADP National Employment Report released Wednesday morning.  The numbers, showing a big downturn in employment, could be one of the few broad-based indicators of the health of the labor market in September if the government shutdown drags on.

headline: US private jobs plunge by 32K in September, ADP reports
summary: ADP reported private company jobs to have declined by 32,000 in September, throwing off experts' expectations of a gain of 51,000. Yahoo Finance senior business reporter Ines Ferré reacts to this data and how it ties back to investor forecasts for the Federal Reserve to further cut interest rates. The US Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) was originally scheduled to report September jobs data this Friday morning, October 3, but this shutdown could delay the release of the report and other key economic data. Certain government agencies' operations will also be temporarily shuttered. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Morning Brief.

headline: October Rate-Cut Odds Hit 100% After Weak ADP Report
summary: Odds of a rate cut when the Federal Open Market Committee meets on from Oct. 28 to Oct. 29 hit 100% in the wake of Wednesday's weak ADP private payrolls report.  Traders see a 99% chance of a quarter-point cut and a 1% chance of a half-point cut, according to the CME FedWatch Tool.
